    "notes": "ExpandPushing for a law which is unpopular with one or more powerful interest groups is the easiest way to create a strong revolution, particularly if the [![IG armed forces.png](https://vic3.paradoxwikis.com/images/thumb/b/b7/IG_armed_forces.png/24px-IG_armed_forces.png)](/Armed_forces \"Armed forces\") Armed Forces is one of them. \n\nFor example, as [![Flag of Japan](https://vic3.paradoxwikis.com/images/thumb/c/c4/Flag_JAP.png/24px-Flag_JAP.png)](/Japan \"Japan\") [Japan](/Japan \"Japan\"), reform the government to include the [![IG intelligensia.png](https://vic3.paradoxwikis.com/images/thumb/d/d1/IG_intelligensia.png/24px-IG_intelligensia.png)](/Intelligentsia \"Intelligentsia\") Intelligentsia, and push for [![Presidential Republic](https://vic3.paradoxwikis.com/images/thumb/2/23/Law_presidential_republic.png/24px-Law_presidential_republic.png)](/Power_structure_laws#Presidential_Republic \"Presidential Republic\") Presidential Republic. The [![IG armed forces.png](https://vic3.paradoxwikis.com/images/thumb/b/b7/IG_armed_forces.png/24px-IG_armed_forces.png)](/Armed_forces \"Armed forces\") Shogunate will be upset and likely launch a revolution. When the revolution begins, during the opening moves phase of the diplomatic play you can switch to play as the revolutionary side. The Shogunate is much stronger than Intelligentsia, so you can easily crush them.\n\nIt is only possible to switch sides in the first phase of the revolution diplomatic play."
